Bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{50%ml} to the boil with @salt{0.25%tsp} for the
rice. When boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{12%minutes}.
Drain in a #sieve{}.

Meanwhile, trim the @pak choi{1} then thinly slice widthways. Roughly chop the
@salted peanuts{25%g}. Roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(stalks and all).
Zest the @lime{1}, then chop into wedges. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated)
(or use a #garlic press{}).

In a #small bowl{}, stir together the garlic, @ginger puree{1%tbsp}, @teriyaki
sauce{75%ml} and half the lime juice. Add the water, stir together and set aside.

Heat a splash of @oil{a splash} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. When
hot, add the pak choi and stir fry until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Remove the
pak choi to a #bowl{} and pop your pan back on high heat. Add a drizzle of
@oil{a drizzle} and the @diced chicken breast{260%g}, stir-fry until browned
all over, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Lower the heat to medium then pour the sauce into the pan. Cook, coating the
chicken in the sticky sauce, for ~{2-3%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The chicken is
cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if it dries out too much.

Meanwhile, in a #large bowl{} gently toss together the cooked rice, lime zest,
pak choi, half the coriander and half the peanuts. Season to taste with
@salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Divide the rice between plates and serve the sticky chicken on top of it.
Finish by pouring any sauce left in the pan over the top and scattering over
the remaining peanuts and coriander. Top with the remaining lime wedges for
squeezing over. Enjoy!

> Step 4 MOD: If you have chosen diced chicken breast instead of pork, cook the
> chicken the same as you would have cooked the pork in the step above and in
> the rest of the recipe. IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink
> in the middle.